FT  03 JAN 92 / International Company News: Axa to buy US space insurance
specialist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AXA, the large French insurance group, announced yesterday that it was
acquiring privately-owned International Technology Underwriters (Intec), a
Maryland-based company which specialises in arranging space insurance.
No financial details for the deal were announced. Intec added that it had
yet to be determined whether Axa would have 100 per cent ownership, although
it confirmed that the French insurer would take a majority stake.
Intec, which employs around 17 people and handles around 15 to 20 large
policies a year, is essentially a managing general agent for space insurance
on behalf of CIGNA, the US multi-line insurer. It said it expected this
operational arrangement to be unaffected by Axa's involvement.
News of the deal came mid-afternoon in New York, and there was no immediate
comment from Axa.
A spokesman for the French company, however, said that Mr Claude Bebear, Axa
chairman, had long been interested in certain high-technology niche sectors
of the insurance industry.
Last year, Axa made its long-sought significant investment in the US when it
injected Dollars 1bn into Equitable Life, the mutual life insurer.
