<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JAN 92 / Tax burden rises, official figures show: Publication of
Treasury statistics suppressed for 18 months, says Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government suppressed figures showing that the poll tax has
significantly increased the tax burden on many households, Labour said last
night.
Treasury data on the impact on typical households of the poll tax, income
tax, national insurance contributions, VAT and other indirect taxes show
that only single person households or families on above average earnings are
paying a smaller percentage of their incomes in tax than at the end of the
last Labour government in 1979.
Labour asked for the figures in July 1990 but Mr Peter Lilley, then
financial secretary to the Treasury, delayed publication until data on the
poll tax bills actually paid were published last month.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, shadow chief secretary to the Treasury, said: 'I don't
think there is any doubt that the government wanted to suppress the fact
that the poll tax had added to an existing trend.'
The government has admitted that the total tax burden, excluding the poll
tax, has risen for many households, undermining Tory claims to be the party
of lower taxation. The latest statistics, which compare the poll tax with
the old rates system, are likely to embarrass ministers further. Officials
warned, however, that the estimates including the poll tax were only
'approximate'.
The rise in VAT in last March's budget, which has not been included in the
latest figures, almost certainly means the trend of rising taxation will
continue.
Labour used the figures to intensify its attacks on the government's
handling of the economy. Mr Tony Blair, shadow employment spokesman, said
the government's credibility 'has been shot to pieces, first by the creation
of the recession, and then by its arrogant misjudgment of its depth and
extent.'
Mrs Beckett warned that the government may raise VAT again, perhaps to fund
cuts in income tax or increased public spending.
According to the figures, a married couple on average earnings with two
children paid 35.2 per cent of their gross earnings in tax in 1978-79. By
1990-91 that had risen to 37.5 per cent on average earnings of Pounds 306.20
a week. For a married couple, with two children, but earning just three
quarters of average earnings, the rise in the tax burden has been still
greater - increasing from 30.9 per cent of earnings in 1978-79 to 34.9 per
cent in 1990-91.
Of the households sampled, only those on 1 1/2 times average earnings have
seen reductions in the tax burden, Mrs Beckett said.
A family on three quarters average earnings, with two children, paid 6.2 per
cent of their earnings on the poll tax in 1990-91. A similar sized family on
1 1/2 times average earnings paid only 3.4 per cent.
Total personal wealth up sharply since 1976 Page 4
</TEXT>
