<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JAN 92 / Bush puts blame on Japan and EC for trade row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush yesterday rebuffed Australian farmers demanding an end
to US farm subsidies. He declared that the European Community and Japan were
mainly to blame for protectionism in world trade.
On the first leg of his four-nation Pacific tour, Mr Bush also made clear
that he wants Japan to make trade concessions during his talks in Tokyo next
week, particularly by opening its market to the hard-hit US automotive
industry.
Then, early today, while Mr Bush was on a four-hour visit to Melbourne,
Australian mounted police charged into a crowd of about 500 demonstrators
protesting against his presence. Their banners read: 'Stuff Bush's New World
Order'.
The president was then leaving Melbourne for Singapore, the next stage of
his tour.
Mr Bush had earlier faced complaints from more than 3,000 Australian
farmers, outside the federal parliament in Canberra, that US subsidies were
costing them hundreds of millions of dollars a year.
He then delivered a tough trade speech to a joint session of the parliament.
The president told members that US subsidies - known as the Export
Enhancement Programme (EEP) - were needed to offset an 'avalanche' of
subsidised exports by the European Community. The US would not halt the EEP
programme of subsidies until the EC had cut its own export subsidies, he
said.
Asked at a news conference to explain the apparent double standard of
refusing to modify US protectionist policies while demanding big concessions
from Japan, he replied: 'We've never said we're totally pure.'
The EEP programme was the main source of friction in talks in Canberra
between Mr Bush and Mr Paul Keating, the Australian prime minister, who
urged the US to avoid traditional markets for non-subsidised Australian
grain.
The US programme subsidises the disposal of US grain in world markets.
Australia claims this has reduced world grain prices and forced
non-subsidised Australian exports out of traditional markets, notably in the
Middle East, where US sales have increased since the Gulf War.
Mr Bush said the best solution would be an agreement on freer agricultural
trade in the Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
(Gatt) which is expected to conclude shortly.
During his news conference with Mr Keating, Mr Bush sounded much like a
candidate running for re-election, with one eye on the Republican primaries
to come.
He attacked the EC and Japan for unfair trade practices, and singled out
Japan's trade surplus for renewed criticism. The surplus was costing
American jobs and slowing the US recovery, he said.
Mr Bush's tour also takes in South Korea.
Bush ready to wage 'dog-eat-dog' campaign, Page 3
US farming's clouded outlook, Page 14
