<DATE>920103
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JAN 92 / In an age of ink and innocence: Paul Cheeseright reports on
the Pounds 125m management buy-out at the Birmingham Post and Mail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR CHRIS OAKLEY is hoping for the triumph of the innocent. He is the man
who, in November, led the Pounds 125m management buy-out of the Birmingham
Post and Mail.
On financial matters, he confesses to having gone up 'a fairly steep
learning curve'. On further reflection he says it was 'not so much steep as
vertical'.
The buy-out was, after all, the largest UK regional newspaper transaction
for years. It took place against the background of an industry recession
which has cut lifelines of advertising revenue and created difficulties for
other groups with managers more experienced than Mr Oakley.
In any event, as Mr Richard Stott, editor of the Daily Mirror and a buy-out
aspirant himself, reminded readers of The Times last year: 'the road to
management buy-out lies littered with journalistic corpses'.
Just as Mr Stott wishes to pull the Mirror group out of the financial morass
left by Robert Maxwell, so Mr Oakley wanted his company to escape from the
growing capital problems of Ingersoll Publications, the US group which took
control of the Post in 1987. To do that, Mr Oakley, managing director under
Ingersoll, and his team had to pay about twice the sum Ingersoll had spent
four years before.
'Success in the management buy-out was based on ignorance,' Mr Oakley said.
'People find it astounding that six people with no City track record could
raise Pounds 125m.'
But the innocents came away from the City with a package of equity and debt:
Pounds 60m of equity held by Candover, buy-out specialists, and CIN
Ventures, an offshoot of the British Coal pension funds, and Pounds 65m of
borrowings, made up of Pounds 50m of senior debt and Pounds 15m of mezzanine
finance. Within this package there is what Mr Oakley called 'a bit for the
management'.
But there is no equity yet for the staff of the Post. There are no immediate
plans to widen the equity base. 'What we need is a good year's performance
under our belts, and then we can think of the options,' said Mr Oakley.
The staff had little to do with the buy-out. Indeed, they knew little of
what was going on during the months of waiting for Ingersoll to make up its
mind on the technique it would use to reduce debt. That said, when members
of the Oakley team returned from London having completed the buy-out, they
found congratulatory posters stuck on their cars. At the very least there
was relief among the staff that the Americans had gone.
They left a clutch of valuable assets, a larger clutch than the name Post
suggests. The jewel is the Sunday Mercury, the best-selling Sunday paper
outside London with a circulation in Birmingham which exceeds those of all
other Sunday papers there except the News of the World.
The Evening Mail, a breezy tabloid, has stabilised circulation at about
220,000 after enduring falling sales for a decade.
The Coventry Evening Telegraph has locked up its city with a very high
proportion of home sales. There are eight weekly newspapers and a local
listings publication called What's On.
The Sports Argus is one of the few Saturday sports papers and sells more
than 60,000 copies. That circulation is more than double that of the morning
Birmingham Post, the problem paper of the group.
In 1989, the latest year for which accounts are available at Companies
House, the newspaper group made pre-tax profits of Pounds 885,000, down from
Pounds 4.56m the previous year. It had gearing of 132 per cent and was
returning 0.59 per cent on total assets.
But there is more to the company than its titles. It owns its headquarters
building in the centre of Birmingham; this would be worth several tens of
millions of pounds given happier circumstances in the property market.
Ingersoll installed new printing equipment in the building; there are four
presses able to provide high-definition colour, but they are under-used,
with only one occupied every night of the week.
The difficulty for Mr Oakley is both nursing these assets through the
recession and making use of spare capacity. With Pounds 65m of debt to
service, he will be watching his cashflow. Some staff felt that the price
paid for the company would inevitably lead to retrenchment. But Mr Oakley is
clear that 'you don't grow a business by continually cutting away at it'.
Certainly no redundancies have been announced and the only casualty seems to
have been the features editor of the Post. 'Over the next 12 months we're
looking at developing our titles and not cutting them back,' said Mr Oakley.
Probably one quick way of reducing the debt burden would be to sell the
headquarters building and move into cheaper premises. Mr Oakley agreed that
'at some point it may make sense to realise the asset and have a move', but
not yet. Not only is the property market weak, but 'we desperately need a
period of stability; the last thing we now need is a move - it would be
counter-productive'.
The choice then is to slog through the recession. Mr Oakley implied that the
management's backers are patient, that there is time to massage the assets.
There were two principles behind the buy-out, he said.
First, 'we did not draw up a business plan we didn't believe is achievable;
it would have been easy to put forward some tempting figures'. Second, 'when
we looked at the price to be paid we were determined not to end up paying
such a price as to find it impossible to service the debt and pay a return
to the backers'.
Mr Oakley listed some of the immediate corporate targets. He wants, for
example, to have the presses, at Birmingham and Coventry, in use all the
time. That means an expansion of the contract printing business. There is
scope, for example, to undertake the regional printing for a national
newspaper. He wants to strengthen the free-newspaper stable - 'we're not
going to see competitors come into our area unchallenged'.
Then there is the question of the Post, where circulation remains stubbornly
low in spite of a change of editor last year and re-launch as a broadsheet.
Mr Oakley argued that its influence outweighs its sales. He noted that 'it
has a business-dominated readership'. But it seems uncertain of its
constituency, insecure in its identity. Life is uncertain in the amorphous
market area where the styles of the Daily Mail and The Daily Telegraph cross
over, and it is in this ill-defined slot that the Post operates.
Such tasks would be easier in an expanding economy. While the Post has
managed some growth of advertising in the areas it can influence, there is
little it can do about, for example, the sluggishness of the Situations
Vacant columns. The Evening Mail used to advertise 29 pages of jobs two
years ago. Now it is down to 14 or 15.
'We expect to see some improvement in the economy next year, even if it's
not manifest until the second half,' Mr Oakley said. 'We expect advertising
to increase.' There are plenty of other newspaper proprietors who will hope
that he is right.
</TEXT>
