<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JAN 92 / Total personal wealth up sharply since 1976
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOTAL personal wealth in the UK increased more than fivefold between 1976
and 1989, with occupational pensions taking a sharply increased share,
according to government statistics.
The total, including marketable wealth plus occupational and state pension
rights, rose from Pounds 500bn to about Pounds 2,600bn over the period, the
Central Statistical Office says in Economic Trends, published yesterday.
Over the 13 years, there was little change in the overall distribution of
the marketable wealth of individuals. The share of the top 1 per cent fell
slightly, while that of the upper quartile increased a little. The top 1 per
cent owned 21 per cent of the country's wealth in 1976, compared with 18 per
cent in 1989. The top 25 per cent owned 71 per cent in 1976 and 75 per cent
in 1989.
Another study in Economic Trends shows London and the south-east continuing
to have more than their fair share of the national economic cake, although
they experienced below-average growth in 1990.
Provisional figures for gross domestic product (GDP) per head of population
showed wide variations throughout the country, with London at the top of the
scale with Pounds 10,400 and the rest of the south-east with Pounds 9,300.
The highest GDP per head outside the south-east in 1990 was East Anglia with
Pounds 8,400, and the east Midlands with Pounds 8,100. The lowest was
Northern Ireland, at Pounds 6,200 per head.
The figures suggest a continuation of long-term trends, except that the
south-east experienced below-average growth, while the Yorkshire and
Humberside region appears to have grown more rapidly.
Over the past 10 years there has been a significant variation in the
economic performance of the regions. The growth in GDP was most rapid in
East Anglia, followed by the rest of the south-east and the south-west. The
north-west, north and Scotland have grown less strongly, and these regions
contributed a lower proportion of UK total GDP in 1990 than 10 years
earlier.
London's position at the top of the GDP scale in 1989 at 148 per cent of the
national average reflected not only the dominance of the capital as an
industrial and commercial centre, but also the inclusion of commuters'
earnings.
The next-highest GDP per head in a study of areas was Berkshire at Pounds
9,500 (126 per cent of the average), Grampian Pounds 9,100 (120 per cent and
Cambridgeshire and Surrey, both Pounds 8,400 (111 per cent).
At the other end of the scale the GDP per head in Mid-Glamorgan was Pounds
5,400 (72 per cent of average), followed by Merseyside, Cornwall and
Northern Ireland at just over Pounds 5,700 (76 per cent).
A large swathe of northern England is emerging as Britain's most prosperous
area, according to BWD Rensburg, the stockbroking group. Mr John Dyson,
corporate services director, said yesterday a semi-rural 'northern
playground' had emerged, covering an area from the Lake District in the west
to North Yorkshire in the east.
Disposable incomes were often as high or higher than in the most prosperous
parts of the south, but lower unemployment, smaller mortgages on better
property, lower indebtedness, and ease of travel made people feel better-off
than their southern counterparts.
Economic Trends, No 457, Central Statistical Office. HMSO. Pounds 11.
Quarterly Review of Northern Companies. BWD Rensburg, Woodsome House,
Huddersfield HD8 0JG. Pounds 30.
