<DOCNO>FT921-16449</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CACBJACMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920103
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JAN 92 / Russian prices rise far higher than predicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHOCK therapy came to Russia yesterday with prices leaping four or five
times - far more than the doubling predicted by the government for the first
month of the reform.
Shops which last year offered only a few cheap goods were still virtually
bare but the few goods available were now expensive, spelling poverty for
average wage-earners and real hardship for the low-paid.
Ukraine, the second largest republic, also freed its prices yesterday, with
journalists reporting rises of between three and six times, in line with the
Russian experience. Ukraine is to give its citizens Rbs400 worth of coupons
from next week in their salaries as compensation. Belorussia, the third Slav
republic, will free its prices today and will also introduce coupons.
No disturbances were reported in Moscow yesterday, as the price of 10 eggs
rose to Rbs11 from Rbs2, a kilo of indifferent meat to between Rbs21 and
Rbs31 from around Rbs8, and butter to Rbs45 where before it had sold for
Rbs10. The minimum wage and pension is Rbs342 a month.
Mr Yegor Gaidar, the deputy prime minister in charge of economic reform,
told the evening paper Izvestia that price inflation would run at 100 per
cent a month for January and February, and that prices would rise threefold
in the first quarter. Production would fall over the year by 10-12 per cent
and unemployment would rise sharply.
He predicted, however, that the rise in prices would moderate to about 12
per cent a month by the middle of the year and to 'a few per cent' by its
end. He said he feared that political pressures to pay extra compensation
would prove too great to withstand, and that a new inflationary spiral 'in
which money would lose all meaning' would be instituted.
Business people and economists were full of foreboding on the effects of the
price rises - while conceding that the economic situation had become so
desperate that the government had had little choice. Mr Sergei Shibayev,
managing director of the Moscow office of accountants Ernst and Young, said:
'This was the only thing available perhaps to make things better by the end
of the year.'
He added: 'It will give some kind of signal to producers and business: the
problem is that other signals are also being given. The top rate of income
tax is 60 per cent - you cannot create capital in that way.'
Tax rates, agreed in the past few weeks, reflect the government's hunger for
both roubles and hard currency in order to balance the budget, after the
past year in which almost no income came in. Personal income tax bands rise
from 12 per cent to 60 per cent; a new value added tax is set at 28 per
cent; profit tax is put at 32 per cent; and the government has retained the
system under which enterprises which earn hard currency must sell 40 per
cent of it to the government at a low rate.
Mr Mikhail Berger, the chief economic commentator of Izvestia, said the
government hoped to match Poland's experience, with goods coming through to
the shops after a couple of months.
Dr Alexei Kireyev, a former Gorbachev adviser, said both the government and
the population were badly prepared. 'They are already very poor and I think
the therapy may be too shocking for many.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
