<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JAN 92 / Investment banks resign as advisers to Shandwick
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHANDWICK, one of the world's biggest public relations firms, has been hit
by the unexpected resignation of two leading UK investment banks as its
advisers.
Morgan Grenfell resigned as Shandwick's merchant bank and Warburg Securities
quit as its stockbroker just as the City was setting off for its Christmas
holidays.
'Morgan and Warburg felt they had not been kept properly informed about
Shandwick's worsening financial performance', said a financier with a close
knowledge of the deteriorating relationship between the firms.
'We think we kept people properly informed', commented Mr Peter Gummer,
Shandwick's founder, who has been giving public relations advice to Mr John
Major, the prime minister.
Three weeks ago, Shandwick's market value more than halved during a single
day when it announced that it expected to make a Pounds 1m loss for the 15
month period to October 31.
However, only six months ago Shandwick was much more optimistic about its
prospects and announced that interim profits had risen by 12 per cent to
Pounds 8.12m.
Shandwick's share price has plummeted from 145p in late November to 43p last
night, wiping more than Pounds 80m off its market capitalisation.
The financier added that the relationship between Shandwick and the City
firms had been difficult for some time. 'There was a history to their
decision to quit,' he said.
A year ago, Mr Gummer came in for intense criticism from shareholders over a
proposal he put forward to sell 2m of his own Shandwick shares to a scheme
for rewarding his employees - or Esop - at 90p a share.
Shareholders felt the Esop should have offered to buy shares from all of
them, not just from Mr Gummer. In the event, Mr Gummer sold 1.25m shares to
the Esop at the lower price of 51p a share.
Mr Gummer, brother of Mr John Gummer, the Conservative cabinet minister,
said he had already found a replacement for Morgan in the form of Lazard
Brothers and expected to appoint a new stockbroker 'within a matter of
days'.
He blamed a worldwide recession for the deterioration in the firm's
financial performance. In order to cope with the drop in business, he had
had to reduce staff numbers by 200 'very recently', out of 2,000 in total.
Shandwick's rivals are all braced for a difficult year, following the rapid
expansion of their industry during the 1980s.
It is understood, however, that Warburg retains confidence in Mr Gummer's
ability to groom its image and is keeping the firm as its own public
relations adviser.
</TEXT>
