<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JAN 92 / Letter: No position for an unqualified assertion on pensions
rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MICHAEL ELTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I have not suggested, as Bryn Davies (Letters, December 30) implies,
that in the Barber case the European Court of Justice changed the law as
opposed to interpreting Article 119 of the Treaty of Rome.
The court did, however, conclude that with limited exceptions 'the direct
effect of Article 119 of the Treaty may not be relied upon in order to claim
entitlement to a pension with effect from a date prior to that of this
judgment' (May 17 1990).
Although - indeed because - these words are open to further interpretation
by the European Court, I certainly maintain my view that Mr Davies is not in
a position to make the unqualified assertion that the Maastricht protocol
takes away the right of employees to equal pensions from the time when the
UK acceded to the treaty (January 1 1973).
Michael Elton,
director general,
National Association of Pension Funds,
12-18 Grosvenor Gardens,
London SW1W 0DH
</TEXT>
