<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JAN 92 / Aviation insurers face crash claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO AIR crashes over Christmas have left London aviation insurers with
multi-million dollar claims, aggravating losses in the market and adding to
pressure for increases in aviation insurance rates, Richard Lapper writes.
Premiums have been rising steadily over the past three months after reaching
their lowest level since the early 1980s earlier this year.
Mr Jonathan Palmer-Brown, an aviation insurance broker at Nicholson
Chamberlain Colls, said the claims 'will increase the pressure for rate
rises'. He added: 'A lot of cash will come out of the market.'
The crash on Sunday of a Boeing 747-200F jet freighter, operated by China
Airlines, followed hard on the heels of the loss of a Swedish airliner on
Boxing Day.
The Chinese aircraft, en route to Anchorage, Alaska, plunged into a mountain
soon after taking off from the Taiwanese capital, Taipei.
Nicholson Chamberlain Colls expects claims for the aircraft's hull to be at
least Dollars 60m (Pounds 32m).
On Friday a McDonnell Douglas MD81 jet airliner, operated by Scandinavian
Airlines Systems, broke up when it crash landed after both its engines
failed on take off from Stockholm's Arlanda airport. It was insured for
Dollars 35m.
</TEXT>
