<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JAN 92 / Business leaders predict gloom for election year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, RACHEL JOHNSON, ROBERT PESTON, LISA WOOD, IAN HAMILTON
FAZEY, RICHARD DONKIN and ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S election campaign over the next six months will be fought against
a background of deep economic gloom, according to leading economists, chief
executives and trade union leaders, write FT reporters.
In a Financial Times survey of new year forecasts published today, most of
the 23 groups of economists from the City, universities and independent
think-tanks say the Treasury's November prediction of a 2.3 per cent rise in
gross domestic product this year is too optimistic.
Instead, the average forecast for output growth is about 1.7 per cent
between 1991 and 1992, with unemployment likely to climb to 2.7m. With the
pound continuing to struggle as the weakest currency in the European
exchange rate mechanism (ERM), the government may face having to take the
politically unpopular step of raising interest rates from their current 10.5
per cent. This follows the increases made by other ERM members just before
Christmas.
In the FT survey, economists generally take a bullish view of prospects for
interest-rate cuts in the longer term. They expect rates to have fallen to
9.5 per cent by the end of 1992, with retail price inflation at a
year-on-year rate of 3.7 per cent. However, these potentially positive
points appear elusive to many industry leaders. Mr Peter Bonfield, chairman
and chief executive of ICL, the UK computer group owned by Fujitsu of Japan,
said the next 12 months would be 'extremely tough'.
While Sir Denys Henderson, chairman of Imperial Chemical Industries,
believes 1992 will usher in 'modest' growth, Sir Antony Pilkington, chairman
of glassmaker Pilkington, said: 'For planning purposes, we are assuming that
1992 will be much the same as 1991.'
From the banking world, Mr Peter Burt, chief general manager of the Bank of
Scotland, said: 'There is is not yet any sign of an improvement in economic
conditions.' Sir John Quinton, chairman of Barclays Bank concurred. He said
1991 saw the 'worst collapse' of business confidence since the 1930s.
Prospects were little better for the new year. Mr Brian Pearse, chief
executive of Midland Bank, said ministers could take an important step to
revive the economy by calling an early election. Consumer spending was
unlikely to increase before people knew whether they would have to pay
higher taxes under Labour, he said.
Small businesses will continue to have a tough time, said Mr John Townend
MP, chairman of the smaller business committee of Conservative backbenchers.
The long period of high real interest rates was still exerting a
'debilitating' effect on many small companies, he said.
Mr Roger Bootle, of Greenwell Montagu, said: 'The man in the street may not
see any economic improvement at all because all the things he knows and
cares about - unemployment, house prices and business failures - will still
be getting worse.'
Some are arguing that the government should change tack. Mr Michael
Saunders, an economist at the London office of Salomon Brothers, the US
investment bank, says Mr Lamont should refrain from referring to a recovery
in the not-too-distant future, and instead 'start to prepare people
psychologically for the difficult period over the next two years during
which growth will be extremely muted'.
Mr John Shepperd, an economist at SG Warburg Securities, said: 'People are
still struggling with the large hangover of debt from the economic boom of
the 1980s. This hasn't been a normal recession, and we won't see a normal
recovery.'
The picture is little different seen from the perspective of trade unions.
Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union, said business
confidence had yet to return and more large-scale redundancies were in
prospect. Mr Gavin Laird, general secretary of the AEU general union, said:
'Everybody I speak to is immersed in gloom.'
Most economists see end to recession in 1992 Page 4
</TEXT>
