<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is one of those rare nights when I am glad to be a television critic and
consequently in receipt of preview cassettes. At 8.00 Channel 4 begins a 3
hour 20 minute repeat of David Freeman's much-discussed Opera Factory
production of Cos fan tutte, transferred from an 18th century Neapolitan
cafe to a 20th century Mediterranean beach. Then at 8.30 ITV begins a
two-hour Sherlock Holmes special: 'The Master Blackmailer'. This series has
been consistently outstanding, shot on good locations, with excellent casts.
Today, in addition to Jeremy Brett and Edward Hardwicke playing Holmes and
Watson as usual, the cast includes Robert Hardy, Gwen Ffrangcon-Davies, and
Nickolas Grace. Then, just to make life impossible, BBC2 begins a promising
series at 8.30 called Perpetual Motion. It will be considering six forms of
transport which 'refused to die', starting with the Morris Minor. It is also
Jodie Foster's night. At 6.00 she features in the odd and not entirely
satisfactory 'gangster movie' Bugsy Malone (BBC2) in which all parts are
taken by children. Then at 10.00, in The Accused (BBC1), she has the key
role of a girl who is gang-raped after behaving 'provocatively' in a bar.
</TEXT>
