FT  02 JAN 92 / Managers urge education boost
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN Lamont, the chancellor, should plan for more spending on
education, training and transport in his March Budget rather than cut taxes,
the British Institute of Management says.
In its pre-Budget submission to the Treasury the institute has asked Mr
Lamont to delay tax cuts until Britain's investment in these areas equals
that of its European competitors. In particular, it urged the chancellor to
extend tax relief to more people attending training courses on their own
initiative.
The institute also urged more spending on the railways and public transport.
It called for simplification of the tax system with measures including the
amalgamation of national insurance and income tax contributions.
The suggestions were based on the responses of 730 managers to a
questionnaire.
