<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Glaxo scientists sign personal
contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GLAXO, the pharmaceuticals company, said that 60 per cent of a group of
scientists at its Barnard Castle, Durham, site have signed personal
contracts in spite of opposition by a union fighting to preserve its
recognition agreement there.
Signing the contracts will result in the scientists depending for pay rises
on their individual performance.
The Association of Management and Professional Staffs said that in a recent
ballot among the 80-strong group, members voted by 11 to one against
continuing a performance-related pay system introduced two years ago.
It accused the company of reneging on an agreement, made at the time of the
introduction of performance pay, that the scientists could revert to
traditional pay bargaining systems if they wished.
Mr Tony Casey, executive secretary of AMPS, said that only about 30 per cent
of members had signed the contracts. Although there was no mood for
industrial action, the scientists were extremely angry about the company's
attitude.
Glaxo said it was encouraging people to take time to make up their minds on
the personal contracts.
Scientists at two other plants in Glaxo Manufacturing Services are also
being offered personal contracts. The company said it wanted to standardise
an individual relationship between staff and itself throughout the graduate
and professional groups in GMS. It denied that it had reneged on any
previous agreement, saying the contracts issue was totally separate.
</TEXT>
