<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JAN 92 / TSB launches code for small businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TSB, BRITAIN'S sixth-largest bank, is to announce details of its banking
code for small-business customers on Monday.
Included in the code of practice are commitments to notify customers in
advance of changes to quarterly banking charges, and to publish its basic
framework of tariffs for the larger of its small-business customers.
TSB is the fifth bank to unveil a business-banking code after strong
criticism of lenders last summer for their alleged poor treatment of
small-business customers. The code also applies to its Hill Samuel merchant
bank subsidiary.
The bank was not one of those called in to see Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, to explain their actions last summer. However, it has decided to
follow the big four high street banks - Barclays, Lloyds, NatWest and
Midland - in publishing a code to emphasise its role as a provider of
finance to business.
A brochure outlining the code of practice will be available from TSB
branches from January 6.
The code promises fair terms and conditions in contracts with customers.
Contracts will be written in plain language. The bank will give reasonable
notice of any changes in contract terms. Advance notification of charges
will be introduced later in the year after computer modifications.
TSB will also ask customers who negotiate an overdraft or loan to sign and
return a letter acknowledging acceptance of the terms and conditions. It
believes this will bring home to customers the obligations they are entering
into.
As well as providing customers with details of its fixed business tariffs,
which currently apply to companies with a turnover of up to Pounds 250,000,
the bank will publicise its tariffs applying to larger businesses. These
tariffs remain negotiable, but TSB said the publishing of basic rates would
give customers a basis for negotiation instead of dealing in the dark.
</TEXT>
